					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tgjer" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1649421); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1649421&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204273" alt="tgjer" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1649421)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tgjer" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1649421); return false;" >tgjer</a></span> <span class="odate time_1410198693 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Sep 2014 17:51</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2105277">
									

<p>Idk, I've always imagined Wondertainment not as lacking morals so much as having <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlueAndOrangeMorality">blue/orange morality</a>. There do seem to be standards and priorities guiding Wondertainment's actions, but they're very alien and we have only vague ideas of what they might be.</p>
<p>That said, this is pretty dark. I like the idea that Wondertainment may be both desperate and under an unknown level of influence from the far more malevolent seeming Factory. For unknown reasons he needs an heir *right now* no matter the cost, someone who can do something he can't, which is pretty terrifying given how powerful he already was.</p>

